    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "right, i get the distance thing. so if i use min-max scaling to squash everything between 0 and 1, that fixes it, right? but what about gradient descent? i know some people use standardization (z-score) instead of min-max. why does the scale of the features actually impact how fast the optimization converges? like, does it change the shape of the cost function surface?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The scale of your features absolutely changes the shape of the cost function surface, and it does so in a way that is far more subtle than just \"making the numbers look nicer.\" If you don't normalize your data, the optimization landscape for gradient descent becomes **highly non-convex**, often with **multiple local minima** and a very **steep, jagged terrain**.\n\nImagine your cost function as a landscape you are trying to roll a ball down. If your features are raw income and age, the \"terrain\" is dominated by the income axis. The surface will look like a massive, rolling hill where the income axis is the vertical height and the age axis is the horizontal width. The ball will roll down this hill incredibly fast, but it might get stuck in a tiny, useless valley near the bottom of the income axis before it even reaches the global optimum.\n\nIf you apply **min-max scaling** (squashing income and age to 0-1), you are essentially flattening this entire landscape. The income axis is now just a tiny, flat strip on the side, and the age axis is a wide, gentle slope. The ball rolls down much more smoothly, and the path to the global optimum is much",
      "source": "target",
